{{Infobox person | name = Peter Wilson | birth_name = | birth_date = 1958 | birth_place = [[Belfast]] | death_date = 1 August 1973 | disappeared_place = [[Northern Ireland]] | monuments = | nationality = [[Irish people|Irish]] }}
'''Peter Wilson''' (1952 – 1 August 1973) was a man from [[Northern Ireland]] who was abducted and killed by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]]. The IRA never gave any explanation for his abduction and murder. His body was not found for 37 years, and he was listed as one of [[Disappeared (Northern Ireland)|the Disappeared]] by the [[Independent Commission for the Location of Victims' Remains]].
==Disappearance== Wilson, a native of West [[Belfast]], with five siblings, was described as "a vulnerable man with learning difficulties".<ref name="belfasttelegraph1">{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/northern-ireland/peter-wilson-disappeared-by-the-ira-found-at-the-beach-his-family-treasured-14994067.html|title=Peter Wilson: 'Disappeared' by the IRA, found at the beach his family treasured|publisher=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|date=3 November 2010|accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref> He was abducted by the IRA in the summer of 1973, somewhere in the St. James area of Belfast, and killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/alpha/W.html|title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths|publisher=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref> Only in 2009 was he added to the list of Northern Ireland's 'Disappeared'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-10814888|title=BBC News - Who were the 'Disappeared'?|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|date=28 June 2011|accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref> His body was located at the beach in [[Waterfoot, County Antrim]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/peter-wilson-disappeared-by-the-ira-found-at-the-beach-his-family-treasured-28568519.html|title=Peter Wilson: 'Disappeared' by the IRA, found at the beach his family treasured - BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-08-25|language=en}}</ref> on 2 November 2010, the day after excavations began following the receipt of "reliable and high quality" information. His family had often walked on the beach, unaware that he was buried there.<ref name="belfasttelegraph1"/> Wilson was the ninth of the known "Disappeared" to be located since 1999.<ref name="belfasttelegraph1"/>
