{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}} {{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}} '''Jai Abberton''' (born ''ca'' 1973 in [[Maroubra, New South Wales|Maroubra]], [[New South Wales]]), an [[Australia]]n former professional [[surfer]], is a member of the Australian surf group, the [[Bra Boys]]. He rose to local prominence in 2005, when he was charged but found [[Acquittal|not guilty]] of the 2003 murder of stand-over man, Anthony 'Tony' Hines.<ref name="surfermag.com">{{cite news | url = http://www.surfermag.com/features/onlineexclusives/kobyabbertonprofile/ | title = Bra Boys: The often maligned surf brotherhood's new movie | work = [[Surfer Magazine]] | publisher = Interlink Media | author = ''Surfermag'' | date = 22 July 2010 | accessdate = 6 February 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/07/23/1090464839797.html | title = Bra Boy murder: pro-surfer's brother 'lured victim' | work = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]] | agency = [[Australian Associated Press|AAP]] | date = 23 July 2004 | accessdate = 6 February 2011}}</ref> Despite Abberton admitting to shooting Hines, Abberton claimed that he had no choice as Hines was going to rape the girlfriend of Abberton, and kill them both. Abberton's defence was able to establish reasonable doubt of murder and that Hines was a violent man that employed standover tactics and was a rapist. It was alleged that the motivation for Hines' actions was a mistaken belief that Abberton had slept with Hines' wife, Rachel Gibbons.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.smh.com.au/news/National/Surf-gang-member-cleared-of-standover-mans-murder/2005/05/05/1115092629172.html | title = Surf gang member cleared of standover man's murder | work = The Sydney Morning Herald | publisher = Fairfax Media | author = Wallace, Natasha | date = 6 May 2005 | accessdate = 6 February 2011 }}</ref>
Abberton was convicted [[trial in absentia|''in absentia'']] by Magistrate Linden and fined $533; prosecutors allege that Abberton was tasered three times in the course of the incident, which occurred at the Byron Bay police station, following Abberton handing himself to police following damage to a caravan and a domestic incident. The Court was also advised that Abberton was admitted to a mental health unit after this incident but has only recently been kicked out of a north coast NSW [[drug rehabilitation]] centre, Bennelong's Haven, after testing positive to having the narcotic, opiate, in his system.<ref>[http://www.goldcoast.com.au/article/2012/07/06/429681_tweed-byron-news.html], Tweed News, Goldcoast.com.au, retrieved 6 Jul 2012</ref>
Together with his brothers, [[Koby Abberton|Koby]], [[Sunny Abberton|Sunny]], and [[Dakota Abberton|Dakota]], Jai Abberton achieved national and international attention in 2007<ref name="indep">{{cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/australasia/sydneys-notorious-surf-gang-turns-tide-of-violence-into-bigscreen-adulation-440840.html | title = Sydney's notorious surf gang turns tide of violence into big-screen adulation | date = 19 March 2007 | author = [[Kathy Marks|Marks, Kathy]] | work = [[The Independent]] | publisher = Independent Print Limited | accessdate = 16 November 2008 }}</ref> with the release of a feature-length documentary entitled ''[[Bra Boys: Blood is Thicker than Water]]'', written and directed by members of the Bra Boys.
